	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>What's causing the problem with the portal stones is the increased ease of getting to zones with experience modifiers.  Since most players seem to be trying to level as quickly as possible, they all head to zones like Paludal Caverns when they're in the right level range.  That means if you're between 15 and 25 and want to group, you have to go to Paludal Caverns because there won't be anyone in other zones.  I had to go there myself when I didn't feel like soloing.  Back when I finished with that zone, the next point that seemed to be attracting lots of players was Marus Seru.  Last week I went out to farm hopper hides and I was the only one there.  At level 39 it seems that my grouping choices are now limited to easy LDoN adventures from the Butcherblock camp or occasional trips to Dawnshroud.<br />
<br />
I don't think shutting down the portals would really help though.  I started my character in Qeynos and I've covered most of Antonica in my travels.  I don't know how this worked for the old-timers, but the first time I zoned into High Hold Pass I was immediately attacked by several orcs that were blue to me at 24.  I won the fight, but if I hadn't had an easier method of travel available to me I'd probably never have bothered going as far as Freeport.<br />
<br />
In my opinion the main issue is the idea that only the high level game is worth playing.  It's all a race to the top with no concern for what's in between.  What would probably reduce this idea would be an increased number of quests made for low and mid level characters, most likely centering on the home cities, and having items with spell focus effects that can be obtained before they're obsolete.  I don't want to have to rush into the end game, and if there are enough things I can do at lower levels I won't have to.  I have nothing against the high end raiding guilds, and I'm not going to suggest that casual players need to have access to equivalent gear without raiding.  I do think that the developers need to include plenty of content to keep the interest of casual players though.  In LDoN they introduced the Adventurer's Stone that gains power with the number of completed missions.  Why can't they add similar progressive quests that start in the old world cities?  I know there are some progressive quests already, but many of the rewards don't compare all that well with gear that can be obtained cheaply in the Bazaar.  This would give some reward to people who stick to a home base instead of following the hot zones, and it would provide interesting challenges and goals to players who haven't yet ventured into the planes.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
